shortDescription: Learn to identify the sneaky sugars hiding in carbs and how they affect your health.
longDescription:
This HealthQuest will show you how foods high in carbohydrates, such as breads, potatoes, and pastas, can affect your blood sugar and your overall health.

Over the course of four sessions, you'll identify some of your triggers (in other words, why you're eating carbs), and try out some tweaks<&mdash>small ways to cut back, little by little. You'll come away with a new approach to carbs in just four to eight weeks.

resourceList.title: 10 Convenient Low-Carb Snacks
resourceList.description: Consider this the perfect place to start brainstorming healthy work snacks that you can simply buy or quickly prepare.

resourceList.title: American Heart Association: Recipes
resourceList.description: While not everything here is low-carb, you can search by "Ingredients" to get recipes focused on meat and vegetables (versus pasta and grains). Click on the View Full Nutrition Info link on any recipe to see the carb count.

resourceList.title: American Diabetes Association: MyFood Advisor
resourceList.description: A wonderful resource for people with or without diabetes, this site contains meal plans and even a handy grocery list generator. Check back often to see new featured recipes.

resourceList.title: USDA Food Composition Databases
resourceList.description: Check carbohydrate counts for common foods and ingredients.

alternativesList.description:
• Always, always make a list. You can go old-style and do it on paper, email it to yourself, or even get fancy and download a dedicated app. Then, stick to your list.
  • If you're not the primary grocery shopper in your house, consider taking that duty over...unless your partner has also committed to the low-carb life!
  • Avoid shopping on an empty stomach. Hunger and low blood sugar can easily cloud your judgment and make you prone to impulse buys. If you can't avoid it, chew a piece of sugar-free gum to take your mind off your hunger.
alternativesList.subHeader: It's hard to eat what you don't have! So consider every grocery store run an opportunity to set yourself up for success in the days to come. Here are a few tips to get you started.

alternativesList.description:
